#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Array
{
private:
    int arr[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};

public:
    int& operator[](int index)
    {
        return arr[index];
    }
};

int main()
{
    Array ob;

    cout << ob[2] << endl;   // 30

    ob[2] = 100;

    cout << ob[2] << endl;   // 100

    return 0;
}

ob[2]

Compiler converts it to:

ob.operator[](2);

operator[] overloads the subscript operator.

It allows objects to be accessed like arrays.

Returning int& allows both reading and writing.

Why is operator[] a member function?
operator[] must be a member function because
the left operand must be the object itself.

Example:

ob[2]

becomes

ob.operator[](2);
